author: kessel0222
body:
Hi,


First time investor here and I’m in a kind of limited choice situation due to my country's (Thailand) retirement scheme. Basically I can invest 30% of my income and deduct the investment from my taxable income. This alone will give me a 10% return just from tax savings.


Unfortunately, I’m also forced to pick from the very limited offerings of the local banks.

I’d like to invest in SPY, ACWI-ex-US and MSCI emerging markets.


From what’s available, I found a S&P500(TER 1.1%) and an ACWI(TER 0.6%). An ACWI-ex-US is not available, so I would be exposed to the US with both, as the ACWI has 60% US stocks on its own already. In that situation, would you go with both or only ACWI since it has enough US exposure already?


Also, I’ve been advised that I should put 20% into bonds for now as there is too much liquidity in the market from covid and then shift it into index funds if/when a contraction happens.


Basic Info:


35 yo

Thailand

No debt

No savings :(

Objective and horizon: Keep the money in a diversified passive index and dont touch until retirement

Risk tolerance: Moderate I guess. I’m expecting indexes to go up and down quite a bit over the decades and just want to wait them out without actively trying to beat the market.

author: Striking-Help-8132
body: Kindly note the the TER does not represent the only costs involved. There is also the bid/ask spread which is caused by the trading process and heavily influenced by the liquidity of the ETF you are intending to buy or sell. These spreads are huge sometimes at smaller funds which are just covering a niece market (e.g single countries or sectors). This is one of the reasons why you might prefer a ETF from an larger player over one which has a cheaper TER. There is no free lunch on the capital market ;)

author: litshit94
body:
An example: one ETF costs 100$ and has 1% TER. So the real price in the first year you buy the ETF is 100$-1%, while you only buy or sell them (to simplify there is no spread) at 100$.
Now imagine the ETF performs 0% in one year. Then the price will drop to 99$, because the ETF Manager had to pay themselves.

We never really see the costs of TER. They are included in the price. It has a similar effect on the price like a dividend payout on the ex-day.

Maybe I am overthinking, but like Buffet said: "never loose money!"

I am trying to understand the rationale behind rejecting a fund with 3% TER, even if it produces a better return over time, as compared to one with 0.03% TER but a lower return.

author: InterestingRadio
body:
The US market is 63% or something of the developed market equity universe, so if you in addition buy a SP500-tracker you are essentially overweighting USA, and this exposes you to US-specific idiosyncratic risk. Since idiosyncratic risk can be eliminated by diversification, this would arguably represent uncompensated risk. I.e. not a sensible choice. 

If you have access to it through your broker, you could also probably construct that portfolio cheaper by buying individual ETFs and manually rebalancing. A bit more hassle, but then again, more for you in investor returns than lost to fees.

Amundi Prime Global has 0.05% TER, combined with iShares Core  Emerging Market IMI (0.18%) and iShares World Small Cap (0.35%) held at 80/10/10 means total cost of ownership before securities lending income in the funds is at 0.07%, much cheaper than the Vanguard fund.

If you do choose the Vanguard fund, that is also perfectly fine and a good choice

author: Striking-Help-8132
body: Don’t look just on the TER. Smaller ETFs with a tiny capitalization are cheaper, but you typically pay a higher bid/ask spread when buying and selling the thing. That’s one of the advantages if you go with the major guys like Vanguard or iShares...

body: Texas Instruments is awesome. Their product portfolio consists of >100k products sold over an equally large number of customers so a very diverse revenue stream. Not only that, they make analog chips which have very long sell cycles. The latest Samsung or Apple chip may only be relevant for a year or 2 before faster/better chips are made but analog chips have 7 to 10 year sell cycles. $TXN still sells a chip that they designed/manufactured 30 years ago! And, it's vertically integrated. Great business.

author: creemeeseason
body:
I've been eyeing ADI (analog devices) or TXN (Texas instruments). They make analog chips instead of digital and have a virtual duopoly. Analog chips have a long life cycle, sometimes 10 years plus, so these companies aren't in a constant technology cycle race. As a result they basically mint money off existing tech. 

Not as glamorous, but their chops go into everything. 5g, cars, phones, satellites, industry... basically all growing fields.

author: Kva1234
body:
I'm from El Salvador, and this could be nothing but a lie. Yes, a lot of people receive remittances, but transmitting dollars doesn't cost 50% in fees. If you're sending money from the US to here, you barely pay normal western Union fees, which are like $8 for every $100. People over here are not educated enough to know the risks this move implies for our population. 

Currently, this idiot cut ties with OAS and is looking to cut ties with the US and have China as our main economic partner, just as Nicaragua did (take a look at their economy and see how they're doing). This is a disaster, uneducated population taking on high risk speculation, while cutting ties with the country that supplies 80% of our oil, for one that enslaves its people.

This move will basically make El Salvador safe haven for the corrupt ones in the world because it wouldn't be possible to trace their stolen money to have them accountable for something. By cutting ties with OAS, we're becoming a no-extradition country. The worst part is, ignorant people who voted for him still supports this crap even after being explained to.
